0","1482":"1482","1382":"1382","1419":"1419","1380":"1380","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","London Middlesex England":"London, Middlesex, England"},"en":{"1375–1452":"1375–1452","1380–Female":"1380–Deceased","1403–1482":"1403–1482","1350–1419":"1350–1419","1355–Female":"1355–Deceased","1403":"1403","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1452":"1452","1374":"1374","1350":"1350","1482":"1482","1382":"1382","1419":"1419","1380":"1380","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","London Middlesex England":"London, Middlesex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Williamson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Northern) and Scottish: from the Middle English personal name   William   + patronymic <i>-son</i> ‘son of <i>William</i>’. This surname is also found in Northern Ireland (Ulster), especially in Antrim.","Americanized form of Norwegian, Danish, and North German   Wilhelmsen  , Swedish <b>Wilhelmsson</b>, or Dutch and North German   Willemsen  , all cognates of 1.","History: This surname was brought to North America from northern England and northern Ireland independently by numerous different bearers from the 17th century onward. Timothy Williamson is recorded in Plymouth Colony in 1643."],"variants":[{"name":"Willamson","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Williamson  ."]},{"name":"William","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English personal name <i>William</i>, <i>Willam</i>, <i>Willem</i>, an Old Picard and Norman French form of ancient Germanic <i>Willihelm</i>, composed of the elements <i>wil-</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm-</i> ‘helmet, protection’. This Norman personal name became widely used in England, Scotland and Wales after the Conquest, mainly no doubt in honor of the Conqueror himself. By the 13th century it had already become the most popular personal name in England. A Parisian form of the name <i>Guillaume</i> was also sometimes used (see   Gillam  ), which in medieval Wales was adopted as <i>Gwilym</i> (see   Gwilliam  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of French   Guillaume  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":7,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Robert Williamson was born in 1375, in Wigmore, Herefordshire, England, his father, Sir William Robertson Williamson, was 25 and his mother, Mrs. William Williamson, was 20. He had at least 1 son with Agnes Williamson. He died in 1452, in his hometown, at the age of 77."},"et":{"1375–1452":"1375–1452","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1403–1482":"1403–1482","1350–1419":"1350–1419","1355–Female":"1355–Surnud","1403":"1403","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1452":"1452","1374":"1374","1350":"1350","1482":"1482","1382":"1382","1419":"1419","1380":"1380","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","London Middlesex England":"London, Middlesex, England"},"fi":{"1375–1452":"1375–1452","1380–Female":"1380–Kuollut","1403–1482":"1403–1482","1350–1419":"1350–1419","1355–Female":"1355–Kuollut","1403":"1403","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1452":"1452","1374":"1374","1350":"1350","1482":"1482","1382":"1382","1419":"1419","1380":"1380","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","London Middlesex England":"London, Middlesex, England"},"fr":{"1375–1452":"1375–1452","1380–Female":"1380–Décédée","1403–1482":"1403–1482","1350–1419":"1350–1419","1355–Female":"1355–Décédée","1403":"1403","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1452":"1452","1374":"1374","1350":"1350","1482":"1482","1382":"1382","1419":"1419","1380":"1380","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Un